Day 13 : Design Pattern
	best practices used by experienced object-oriented software developers
	Creational :::
	Singleton = only one object should be created
	Factory = hiding the object creation logic / how object are internally created (solid o violates)
	Abstract factory design = factory of factories (prevents solid o - ocp violation)
	builder = Useful when an object has many optional parameters or needs to be built in multiple steps.
	prototype = Creates new objects by copying an existing (prototype) object instead of building from scratch.
		- shallow copy = Student s2 = s1 (reference copy) - object is still one
		- deep copy = s2.name = s1.name; (value copy) - different object created

Day 14 : Design Pattern
	Structural :::
	Facade = hide internal structure / complexity
	Decorator = dynamically adds new functionality to an object by wrapping it with another 		    object, without changing the original object's code.
		- decorator = not compulsory (ex. : paneer, cheese in Pizza)
	Adapter = makes incompatable class compatable with interface
	Proxy = Controls access to another object by acting as its substitute.
		- Use Proxy when: I want to control access to an object
	Composite = Treats individual objects and groups of objects in the same way.
		- Use Composite when: I have a tree structure and want to treat single objects 			  and groups uniformly.	
		- File system example (Folder -> Folder -> File)

Day 15 : Design Pattern
	Behavioural ::: object communication
	Observer : Notifies multiple objects when one object's state changes.
		- Use Observer when: I want multiple objects to automatically react to changes 			  in another object.
		- change happen then the task starts (Account money get from ATM -> sms, email, 		  WhatsApp notification send)
	State : Changes an object's behavior based on its current state.
		- Use State when: An object's behavior depends on its internal state and changes 		  over time.
		- changes it's own state
	Strategy : Defines a family of algorithms, encapsulates each one, and makes them 			   interchangeable.
		- Provides different ways to perform the same task.
		- Use Strategy when: You have multiple ways to perform the same task and want to 		  switch the algorithm at runtime without changing the client code.
		- (one employee - different responsibility when intern, jr developer, sr 			  developer)


